availability.p: For internal use by the Faclair na Gàidhlig/DASG projects

note.p: The original reading could well have been "críche", "cum a críche" ("to its end") being a translation of "finaliter".

James Beaton (Hand14) adds a "d" above "tabad". This could be to clarify the meaning of the original suspension stroke or he could have been altering it to tadbad ("appearance"), although how the latter would fit in in terms of meaning is not clear.
The first 6 words of the text are now completely lost but seem to have been well-preserved when Black examined them in the 1970s.
As Black points out, this could either be the noun frecrae or the verb fris-gair. If the latter, it is an example of a lenited Scottish vernacular infinitive without do.
